result.execSummary:
The defendant Tyler W. Shackelford was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Tyler W. Shackelford is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Tyler W. Shackelford was found guilty of Computer Message-Threaten/Injury or Harm, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.0125(2)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
Defendant shall pay a DNA Analysis Surcharge in the amount of $200.00.
Defendant shall pay court costs in the amount of $243.00.

Defendant shall not possess or own a cell phone with a data plan without permission from his probation officer.
Defendant shall not access any site, including email, social media or any other information on the Internet without permission from his probation officer.
Defendant shall not own or possess a computer, laptop, or tablet without permission from his probation officer.
Defendant shall not possess or consume any alcoholic beverages or nonprescription controlled substances, or any prescription medicine for which the defendant does not have a current prescription.
Defendant shall not enter into any establishment where the primary purpose is the sale of alcoholic beverages.
Defendant shall not have any contact of any kind with C.R.D..

Defendant shall consent to a reasonable request of a law enforcement officer, based on probable cause, to submit to a breath, blood, saliva, or urine test for purposes of determining the quantity of alcohol or drugs in defendant's breath, blood, saliva, or urine.
Defendant shall participate in any and all counseling deemed appropriate by the Division of Community Corrections.
Defendant shall abide by all other terms and conditions of probation deemed appropriate by the Division of Community Corrections.
Defendant shall undergo an AODA assessment and follow through with all recommendations thereof.

Pursuant to Sec. 973.015, Wis. Stats., the record of the defendant may be expunged upon a successful completion of probation, and the court making a finding on the record that the person will benefit and society will not be harmed by this disposition.
